%T A397699 2,2,5,2,2,2,2,2,3,2,3,3,2,2,2,2,2,2,3,2,2,2,2,2,2,2,3,2,2,2,5,2,2,2,
%U A397699 2,2,2,3,2,2,2,2,2,2,3,2,3,2,2,2,5,2,5,2
%N A397699 Associated primes of A397698.
%C A397699 If A397698(n) is divisible by p^k (with k maximized) for more than one prime p, a(n) is the largest such p.
%C A397699 Conjecture: All primes appear in this sequence.
%C A397699 From _Michael S. Branicky_, Jul 05 2026: (Start)
%C A397699 The conjecture is likely true (based on an argument by Allan Wechsler; see Links).
%C A397699 Let ok(p, i) denote the following predicate: whether any a(s) = p over all s obtained by deleting a digit from p^i (discarding any resulting s with leading zeros). Empirically, one finds that all primes p < 10^4 satisfy ok(p, 4). (End)
%H A397699 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A397699/b397699.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A397699 Allan Wechsler, <a href="https://groups.google.com/g/seqfan/c/1z8o_QY0_AA/m/RRc5YZGiAwAJ">Prime Powers Sequence</a>, SeqFan mailing list, Jul 05 2026.
%F A397699 a(n) = A356840(A397698(n)). - _Pontus von Brömssen_, Jul 05 2026
%e A397699 A397698(1) = 81 = 3^4; the associated prime is 3, so a(1) = 3.
%e A397699 A397698(21) = 216 = 2^3*3^3; since 3 > 2, a(21) = 3.
%o A397699 (Python)
%o A397699 from sympy import factorint
%o A397699 def f(n): return max((k, p) for p, k in factorint(n).items())
%o A397699 def cands(s): yield from map(int, set(s[:i]+d+s[i:] for i in range(len(s)+1) for d in "0123456789"[int(i==0):]))
%o A397699 def a(n): return sorted(f(t)+(-t, ) for t in cands(str(n)))[-1][1]
%o A397699 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 89)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Jul 05 2026
%Y A397699 Cf. A356840, A397698.
